hold, nearly sixmembers strong when the nation was new, is down statistically tojust over 2{ people, a record low, the Census Bureau said.   The decline reflects ``changes in the age structure of theAmerican population,'' said Census Bureau demographer CampbellGibson in a telephone interview Thursday.   The household is shrinking as families have fewer children, moreyoung people set up housekeeping on their own and the number ofelderly maintaining their own households grows.</TEXT><DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   In the town of Kimry, soap rationing began inApril, limiting each man and woman to one bar of household soap and1} pounds of bath soap in local shops. Not each week or month, buteach year.   The residents of Ufa, a city of 1 million people in the Urals,are loading up on salt and matches due to rumors of pendingshortages.   Sugar rationing went into effect in Moscow on May 1 for thefirst time since World War II, and even the Soviet minister oftrade, Kondrat Terekh, has been issued a card entitling him to 4.4pounds of sugar per month and no more.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House and Senate, upholding amuch-criticized agreement with President Bush, moved towardapproval of $1.2 trillion budget measures which promise to reducethe deficit without cutting spending or significantly raising taxes.   Each chamber rejected several attempts Thursday to overhaul theblueprint for tax and spending policy in fiscal 1990 as theyapproached final votes.   As laid out by the White House agreement, the budgets claim toshrink the federal deficit to just below $100 billion, as requiredby the Gramm-Rudman law. They would allow federal programs to growbut, especially at the Pentagon, at less than the rate of inflation.</TEXT><DATELINE>SELAH, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Tree Top Inc., the nation's largest appleprocessor, announced it will break contracts with growers who usethe chemical Alar on this season's crop.   The growers' cooperative in Idaho, Oregon and Washington saidThursday the move was to assuage consumer fears, which have beeninflamed by allegations about Alar's cancer-causing properties.   In the past, Tree Top rejected apples that were treated with thechemical, which makes apples redder and crisper.</TEXT><DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   California's Supreme Court unanimouslyupheld all of Proposition 103's long-term restrictions on insurancerates and practices, but it punched a hole in a 20 percent raterollback and freeze.   The ruling by the conservative-dominated court Thursday stillwas a serious blow to insurance companies, who had predicted thatProposition 103 would cost them $4 billion a year.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   The stock market recorded another small decline Thursday,continuing its week-long pullback. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials dropped 8.80 to 2,384.90.   The dollar finished at varied levels against major foreigncurrencies.   Bond prices were at a near standstill as traders stayed on thesidelines in anticipation of Friday's release of employment figuresfor April.   Energy futures were mixed as crude oil futures rose overincreased concern with North Sea oil production. Grain and soybeanfutures were mixed; livestock prices were higher and pork futureslower; and precious metals were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>